meta.name: Big Five
meta.description:
Simplified Big Five test with only three domains: ANE (Agreeableness, Neuroticism, Extraversion)
Most people are balanced in EOC (Extraversion, Openness, Conscientiousness). This is why the Big Five test spends three dimensions to find a signal (tendency), where most people say "neutral" or "both".
Why are most people balanced in EOC? This is a result of "normal" education, where children are primarily grouped by same age in pre-school, school, university, even later in work. This will push people to become extreme in Neuroticism (either High or Low), and to become balanced in EOC (Extraversion, Openness, Conscientiousness).
In this Simplified Big Five test, we reduce EOC to one dimension, so in total, we have only three dimensions:
  • A
  • N
  • EOC (high E = high O = low C)
Since most people will say "neutral" for EOC, we place this dimension as the last question.
We use Extraversion and Neuroticism, just like Hans Eysenck does in his two-factor model of personality.
This Simplified Big Five test is still redundant, since high A = (high E and high N) or (low E and low N) = Air or Water.
But we need this third dimension to measure subtype. Why? When either E or N are balanced, then the result is ambiguous. This means we must choose one from two elements. One element will be the "base" element, and the other element will be the subtype ("modality" in astrology).
With High Agreeableness, the "base" element must be either Air or Water, and the subtype element must be either Fire or Earth.
and vice versa: Low Agreeableness → base element is Fire or Earth, subtype element is Air or Water.
